WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.840
Hello!

2
00:00:01.840 --> 00:00:06.280
My name is Nick and I'll be your instructor for this case study in supply chain analytics.

3
00:00:06.280 --> 00:00:11.040
In this case study, you will perform a make versus buy analysis in Power BI.

4
00:00:11.040 --> 00:00:11.040


5
00:00:11.040 --> 00:00:11.080


6
00:00:11.080 --> 00:00:13.960
A case study enables you to apply your skills.

7
00:00:13.960 --> 00:00:18.600
You won’t be learning any new Power BI concepts; instead, you’ll focus on using

8
00:00:18.600 --> 00:00:23.480
the skills you learned in previous courses and practice them on a real-world problem.

9
00:00:23.480 --> 00:00:23.480


10
00:00:23.480 --> 00:00:28.320
This case study uses iterative functions, so it is relatively advanced.

11
00:00:28.320 --> 00:00:33.280
It might help to review iterative functions in DAX before taking this case study.

12
00:00:33.280 --> 00:00:33.320


13
00:00:33.320 --> 00:00:38.120
Below you can see the prerequisites we suggest you take before completing this case study.

14
00:00:38.120 --> 00:00:38.120


15
00:00:38.120 --> 00:00:39.360


16
00:00:39.360 --> 00:00:42.000
So, what is a Supply Chain exactly?

17
00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:45.360
A supply chain is a network of individuals and companies who are

18
00:00:45.360 --> 00:00:49.520
involved in creating a product and delivering it to the consumer.

19
00:00:49.520 --> 00:00:56.000
The Supply Chain begins with the producers of raw material and ends with the product being delivered to the consumer.

20
00:00:56.000 --> 00:00:56.880


21
00:00:56.880 --> 00:00:56.880


22
00:00:56.880 --> 00:01:00.800
For example, a fork begins as a piece of ore from the earth.

23
00:01:00.800 --> 00:01:06.560
The ore is processed into metal, and the metal is formed into the shape of a fork and then polished.

24
00:01:06.560 --> 00:01:09.000
The fork is then packaged and shipped to the consumer.

25
00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:10.040


26
00:01:10.040 --> 00:01:10.040


27
00:01:10.040 --> 00:01:12.880
What do we mean by make versus buy decision?

28
00:01:12.880 --> 00:01:17.920
A good definition is the one from Investopedia: "A make-or-buy decision is an act of

29
00:01:17.920 --> 00:01:22.840
choosing between manufacturing a product in-house or purchasing it from an external supplier."

30
00:01:22.840 --> 00:01:22.840


31
00:01:22.840 --> 00:01:23.840


32
00:01:23.840 --> 00:01:27.000
The make option means manufacturing the product in-house and

33
00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:30.680
the buy option means buying the product from an external supplier.

34
00:01:30.680 --> 00:01:31.920


35
00:01:31.920 --> 00:01:31.920


36
00:01:31.920 --> 00:01:35.280
Another example of a Make versus Buy decision from daily life

37
00:01:35.280 --> 00:01:38.720
is the choice to eat at a restaurant or to prepare lunch at home.

38
00:01:38.720 --> 00:01:38.720


39
00:01:38.720 --> 00:01:39.560


40
00:01:39.560 --> 00:01:43.360
If you prepare your own pizza, that is the Make option.

41
00:01:43.360 --> 00:01:43.360


42
00:01:43.360 --> 00:01:47.080
If you buy a pizza from the local pizza restaurant, that is the Buy option.

43
00:01:47.080 --> 00:01:47.960


44
00:01:47.960 --> 00:01:47.960


45
00:01:47.960 --> 00:01:54.080
Sticking with the tasty pizza analogy, it is clear that the Make versus Buy option has a lot of considerations.

46
00:01:54.080 --> 00:01:54.080


47
00:01:54.080 --> 00:01:54.080


48
00:01:54.080 --> 00:01:56.040
Quality:

49
00:01:56.040 --> 00:01:59.320
Your own pizza might be less tasty than the local Italian restaurant.

50
00:01:59.320 --> 00:01:59.320


51
00:01:59.320 --> 00:02:05.240
Time: Making a good pizza might take you an hour, but ordering a pizza takes 3 minutes.

52
00:02:05.240 --> 00:02:05.240


53
00:02:05.240 --> 00:02:09.360
Cost: You might save money making pizza at home.

54
00:02:09.360 --> 00:02:12.960
But then again, the pizza restaurant might buy pizza ingredients in bulk.

55
00:02:12.960 --> 00:02:13.840


56
00:02:13.840 --> 00:02:13.840


57
00:02:13.840 --> 00:02:19.680
It is clear that with such a complex decision, companies need help quantifying all of these aspects.

58
00:02:19.680 --> 00:02:19.680


59
00:02:19.680 --> 00:02:20.320


60
00:02:20.320 --> 00:02:25.600
For simplicity, this case study focuses on analyzing the cost of the Make and Buy options.

61
00:02:25.600 --> 00:02:32.360
Real companies need to consider quality, time and ethics in their supply chain decision-making.

62
00:02:32.360 --> 00:02:32.360


63
00:02:32.360 --> 00:02:32.360


64
00:02:32.360 --> 00:02:36.440
The skills you learn in the course can also be applied to product lead

65
00:02:36.440 --> 00:02:41.280
times, sustainability and many other factors in the Make versus Buy decision.

66
00:02:41.280 --> 00:02:41.280


67
00:02:41.280 --> 00:02:42.080


68
00:02:42.080 --> 00:02:45.760
The problem you will be working on in this case study is a make versus buy decision.

69
00:02:45.760 --> 00:02:51.240
You are hired as a supply chain analyst at a fictitious company called Tenate

70
00:02:51.240 --> 00:02:56.000
Industries - a company that sells replacement parts for industrial pizza ovens.

71
00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:59.880
Your task is to calculate the full cost of the Make and Buy Options.

72
00:02:59.880 --> 00:03:05.600
You'll be using fictitious data tables of quotes and internal manufacturing estimates.

73
00:03:05.600 --> 00:03:05.600


74
00:03:05.600 --> 00:03:06.440


75
00:03:06.440 --> 00:03:08.840
A quote or a quotation is a document that a

76
00:03:08.840 --> 00:03:15.160
seller provides to a buyer to offer goods or services at a stated price, under specified conditions.

77
00:03:15.160 --> 00:03:15.160


78
00:03:15.160 --> 00:03:15.160


79
00:03:15.160 --> 00:03:19.640
We will start by learning how to analyze costs for the buy option.

80
00:03:19.640 --> 00:03:24.320
In the buy option, we are considering purchasing the products from an external supplier.

81
00:03:24.320 --> 00:03:24.320


82
00:03:24.320 --> 00:03:24.320


83
00:03:24.320 --> 00:03:28.440
In the quotes dataset, you will find that you have quotes from

84
00:03:28.440 --> 00:03:32.720
many suppliers for multiple parts at multiple production volumes.

85
00:03:32.720 --> 00:03:38.400
It is common to quote the same part to many suppliers to ensure the best option is selected.

86
00:03:38.400 --> 00:03:38.400


87
00:03:38.400 --> 00:03:38.400


88
00:03:38.400 --> 00:03:44.600
Each quote line consists of part number quoted, supplier

89
00:03:44.600 --> 00:03:46.640
minimum production volume for the price

90
00:03:46.640 --> 00:03:53.240
quoted, unit cost (per product), non-recurring expenses associated with the minimum production volume.

91
00:03:53.240 --> 00:03:53.240


92
00:03:53.240 --> 00:03:53.240


93
00:03:53.240 --> 00:03:58.000
It is your time to check if you understand the concepts of make versus buy.

94
00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:00.480
After that, we will explore the quote data.

95
00:04:00.480 --> 00:04:03.240
Good luck!

